Frank can be a sweet, loving man in the right situation. When the world isn't screwing him over, undermining his dreams, or demeaning his well-being, he can be a genuinely nice guy. This scene was a great moment. It showed the kind of man Frank is capable of being. Both scenes give layers to Frank's character and a context to his angry outbursts. It's part of what I love about this show. It has steadily established that Frank isn't just angry for the sake of being angry. He has a reason to be upset with how his life has panned out. His dreams of being a pilot were undermined. His boss is a slob. His kids don't appreciate him. Who wouldn't be angry with all that going on? But at the end of the day, he still loves Sue. He still has some good things in his life and that helps keep him balanced...relatively speaking.

Once again, Isaac Arthur takes all the complexities of an issue and presents in a way that is wonderfully engaging. He actually presented some key issues that would arise for those who choose to upload their minds to a digital medium. It has some profound implications for our entire sense of being. And unlike some of the other technologies he discusses, there's nothing too radical about this process. It's just a matter of scale and computing power. When it does become a possibility, we'll have to reckon with the idea that a clump of digital code is a sentient being. What could that mean for humanity? It's fascinating and something I hope gets discussed more.

This movie will always have a special place in my heart. For me, it's one of the best X-Men movies of the Fox era and one of my favorite superhero movies of all time. I get this is not a popular opinion. But I stand by it. I saw Dark Phoenix in theaters the day it came out. It was one of the most satisfying experiences I've had at a movie. Yes, it would've worked best as two movies. That's what Kinberg wanted and I wish he'd gotten that chance. But given the constraints, he really managed to make this work. In a simple, concise story, he showed us how Jean gained all this power, lost control, and used it to save her friends. It captured all the right elements of an X-Men movie. It took moments straight from the source material. And it ended on a hopeful note that ties in nicely with the ending to DOFP. It had its flaws. It certainly wasn't perfect. And it probably would've done a lot better if it had been a two-parter. But I think it worked beautifully in the final product. And I think this movie is going to age better than most expect. Let's face it. We'll never get a movie like this again. Disney would never allow it. They'd never allow a movie like Logan, either. I doubt they'd even let DOFP, given how dark that movie was at times. And even if the X-Men succeed in the MCU, and I believe they will, they'll have that same generic MCU style that has become so common. I think it'll help people appreciate Dark Phoenix even more in the long run. Five years from now, I think it'll be interesting and revealing to revisit this movie and what it achieved before Disney took over.

WRITING.TITLE: Would the cancellation of college football in 2020 help or hurt the XFL?
WRITING.TEXT: I've seen this discussed in multiple threads. I thought I'd simplify it here. At the moment, a good chunk of the major college football conferences have either cancelled their seasons or moved their games to the spring. There's still a chance that we'll see a partial college football season this fall. There's also a chance the whole thing will get cancelled, which could do some irreparable harm to college sports, as a whole. I think the latter outcome is a last resort, but one I think could happen if multiple schools get a surge of positive tests. In that scenario, you've suddenly got a large group of college athletes, many of whom do not have a job or much certainty about their scholarships, in need of work. The XFL, and alternative football leagues in general, may never have a better chance to recruit a huge crop of players who want a chance to show what they can do. Many would likely join as a means of getting into the NFL, but many more may just appreciate a paycheck, which is more than the NCAA will ever give them. I'm now convinced that if this pandemic doesn't prompt the NCAA to pay its athletes, then nothing will. It may ultimately benefit the XFL if college football takes a moral blow this year. It's just a matter of how the league structures itself.
